<font color="#FF0000">DID WE MAKE A DIFFERENCE?</font><br>
<tt>Sun Apr 20 19:57:15 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Professor,<br><br>
Good to see you back. <br><br>
I, like you, feel that what occurred at your Vets organization (6 members quitting) is not the way it should be. It sheds light on one reason why there are ethnic or racial groups who form tightly knit communities. After reading your message I am glad I never joined any Veteran organizations. I couldn't deal with what you described.<br><br>
Please don't see that as a flame from me to you. It is only the reality of where I am coming from.<br><br>
When I relive the war over and over in my mind each day, I never fail to realize that the best part of the experience was the contact I had with the Vietnamese people.<br>
Probably it was the only worthwhile learning I experienced while there.<br><br>
It is unfortunate, in my opinion, that there are those who don't see or didn't see things in the same light.<br><br>
In one of your other posts of today, you mentioned how none of us were perfect. Indeed, I am a textbook example of imperfection. However, on the subject of the people of Vietnam and how they were not well received by your membership, I feel justified in saying that those same members were wrong - not only in their failure to forgive the past, but in allowing their bitterness to dictate such action. Bitterness kills the soul.<br><br>
My advice, as one who served in Vietnam, to anyone who is interested, is to put yourself in the other guys shoes.  <br><br>
Try to imagine if it was your family in harms way for decade upon decade. Try to imagine all of the death and destruction happening in this country. How would you be?<br><br>
It is easy to quit or turn one's back. It is much harder to stay and make things work. There is no question that had those 6 members stayed and gotten to know the Vietnamese  and accepted them, they would have been rewarded 10 fold.<br><br>
My special thanks to Doctor Barry Spatz. He is a prime example of one who is able to stir things quite a bit in this group. Yet, he is also unusually forthcoming in admitting when he is mistaken. As I say he is unusual. And in a very good way. Several threads ago, Doc Spatz made mention of &quot;hoisting a brew&quot; with those who served in the Vietnam War. Someday it might be you and I, Spatz. Hope so anyway.<br><br>
Welp, it looks like this will be one of the last viable threads on this POV site. If it is, good knowing you all. If this site is able to continue, I'll be back.<br><br>
Vaya con Dios.<br><br>
Peace and love is the only way. That concept was established well before the 1960's.<br>

